	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Return to detail of SSM in renewed efforts to work towards ‘rapid conclusion’ of Doha Round</h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>WTO agriculture negotiations reopened in the week of 27 September 2010, at the end of which the chairperson, David Walker, reported that he had begun consultations to clarify specific issues in the December 2008 draft modalities ‘raised by Argentina, China and India in an unofficial paper in May’. Other unofficial papers include ‘Cuba’s call for more flexibility in export credit disciplines for least-developed and net food-importing developing countries’, as well as Costa Rican and Ukrainian concerns regarding the special safeguard mechanism. </p><p>These talks follow a range of less formal discussions at ambassadorial and other levels between May and July, and a WTO report in July that David Walker had had ‘consultations with some members on two areas of substance: the special safeguard mechanism (SSM) that will allow developing countries to raise import duties temporarily to deal with import surges or price falls; and tariff simplification.’ The WTO also noted that in a G20 meeting on 6 July, Canada and Australia had presented ‘road maps’ suggesting a way forward ‘for agriculture as a whole and for cotton’. </p><p>Recent speeches by WTO Director-General, Pascal Lamy, also show renewed efforts to revive the Doha Development Round. First, in a speech to the UN Millennium Development Goals Summit on 20 September, Mr Lamy said that ‘we can and must do better … first of all by working towards a rapid conclusion of the Doha Development Round.’ This, he said, was about ‘delivering for the world’s poorest [and fulfilling] our promises, for example by providing them with duty-free and quota-free market access, or by addressing agriculture subsidies to cotton.’ </p><p>Second, in a speech to the World Trade Institute on 1 October, Mr Lamy observed that ‘the system’s rules have had to become more technical, more intrusive and more binding in order to remain relevant to economies that are still diverse, but far more interdependent.’ He noted that ‘because trade has become so important to development strategies … development is centre stage in the current Doha negotiations.’ While in 1997 80% of disputes were initiated by industrialised countries, in 2010 almost two-thirds of disputes were initiated by developing countries. Mr Lamy suggested that one approach in the current negotiations ‘would be to explore the scope for more plurilateral agreements – allowing smaller groups of Members to move forward, outside the single undertaking, on issues important to them.’ Another approach alongside this would be to build capacity for developing countries, particularly through ‘aid for trade’, to help developing countries ‘to connect with the world economy’. However he affirmed that ‘the central priority remains concluding the Doha Round,’ as ‘bilateral and regional deals can be a complement to the multilateral system, but they can never be an alternative.’</p><p>While some consider that ‘late 2010 and early 2011 may provide a small window of opportunity for a long-delayed breakthrough in the Doha Round’, a number of substantial issues with complex ramifications remain to be resolved.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
