<a href="http://www.euractiv.com/en/food/us-eu-settle-food-fight-anti-counterfeit-pact-news-498472" target="_self">http://www.euractiv.com/en/food/us-eu-settle-food-fight-anti-counterfeit...</a></p><p>ICTSD, ‘Anti-counterfeiting trade pact “99%” complete’, <i>Bridges Weekly Trade News Digest</i>, Vol. 14, No. 34, 7 October 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/86164/" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/86164/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Director-General Lamy’s comments provide an interesting context to the current negotiations. Mr Lamy noted that the practice of dealing with all issues ‘as “single undertakings” – where nothing is agreed until everything is agreed’, in order to give all members in interest in the success of negotiations, can also have the effect of ‘progress on uncontroversial and solvable issues [being] held hostage to progress on more difficult and intractable ones’. His proposal of an approach exploring ‘the scope for more plurilateral agreements’ is therefore of interest.</p><p>One example of a plurilateral agreement is in the recent compromise between the US and EU and other mainly developed countries over the use of geographical indications that are protected in the EU, such as Parma ham or Cognac, addressing EU concerns that trademarks received greater protection than EU products are protected on the basis of defined regional characteristics. The ‘Anti-Counterfeiting Trade Pact’ is ‘over 99% agreed’, according to an EU official, although the provisions are not as strong as WTO intellectual property rules, and discussions on geographical indications are still continuing in the WTO Doha Round. Depending on eventual agreements, seeking geographical indication status may provide an avenue that offers some protection to ACP products that would not be achievable by trademark or other property rights.</p><p>This non-centralised approach can be dangerous for other stakeholders, as for example in the case of the US-Brazil interim agreement on cotton earlier in 2010 (see <i>Agritrade</i> article, ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/en/Commodities/Cotton-sector/News" target="_self">Brazil and US renew interim agreement in their cotton dispute</a>’, August 2010). This reduces pressure to resolve issues in the WTO, leaving West African cotton-producing countries exposed to market volatility. It remains to be seen how the issue of cotton can be taken forward, with Canada and Australia taking an active interest, and ‘addressing agriculture subsidies to cotton’ acknowledged by Mr Lamy as a specific example of a promise that needs to be fulfilled.</p>
		</div>
		
